        <name>10.3.2.1 The exponential form</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;h3&gt;The exponential form&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Since &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(z=r(\cos\theta +i\sin\theta )\)&lt;/span&gt; and since &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(e^{i\theta}=\cos\theta
+i\sin\theta\)&lt;/span&gt; we therefore obtain another way in which to denote a complex number: &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(z=re^{i\theta}\)&lt;/span&gt;, called the &lt;strong&gt;exponential form&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="HELM_keypoint"&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: inherit;"&gt;Key Point&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The exponential form of a complex number is \[z = re^{i\theta}\quad\text{in which}\quad r=|z|\quad\text{and}\quad\theta=\text{arg}(z)\] so \[z=re^{i\theta}=r(\cos\theta + i\sin\theta)\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</questiontext>
